        <link id="build-style-article" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/products/rsna/releasedAssets/css/build-article-8932601a697666afa607.css"/><article xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" data-design="pill" data-has="right-rail" data-type="research-article" vocab="http://schema.org/" typeof="ScholarlyArticle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><header data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><div data-article-access="no" data-article-access-type="other" class="meta-panel"><div class="meta-panel__left-content"><div class="meta-panel__label"><span>Cardiac Imaging</span></div><div class="meta-panel__onlineDate">Jul 11 2016</div></div><div class="meta-panel__right-content"><div class="meta-panel__share"></div></div></div><h1 property="name">Infectious Diseases of the Heart: Pathophysiology, Clinical and Imaging Overview</h1><div class="contributors"><span class="authors"><span class="heading">Authors</span>: <span role="list"><span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con1"><span property="givenName">Horacio</span> <span property="familyName">Murillo</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, PhD</span></a> <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection#533b3c2132303a3c7d3e26213a3f3f3c13343e323a3f7d303c3e" property="email" aria-label="Email address"><span class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="e28a8d9083818b8dcc8f97908b8e8e8da2858f838b8ecc818d8f">[email&#160;protected]</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con2"><span property="givenName">Carlos Santiago</span> <span property="familyName">Restrepo</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con3"><span property="givenName">Juan Alejandro</span> <span property="familyName">Marmol-Velez</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con4"><span property="givenName">Daniel</span> <span property="familyName">Vargas</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con5"><span property="givenName">Daniel</span> <span property="familyName">Ocazionez</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con6"><span property="givenName">Santiago</span> <span property="familyName">Martinez-Jimenez</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con7"><span property="givenName">Robert Lee</span> <span property="familyName">Reddick</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, and <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con8"><span property="givenName">Ameya Jagdish</span> <span property="familyName">Baxi</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span></span></span><a href="#tab-contributors" class="to-authors-affiliations" data-id="article-authors-viewall">Authors Info &amp; Affiliations</a></div><div class="core-self-citation"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span class="heading">Publication</span>: <span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">36</span></span><span class="delimiter">, </span><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">4</span></span></div><div class="doi"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2016150225" property="sameAs">https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2016150225</a></div></div><div class="info-panel"><div class="info-panel__left-content"><div class="info-panel__metrics info-panel__item"></div></div><div class="info-panel__right-content"><div class="info-panel__article_tools info-panel__item">



        
        <div class="article-tools"><a href="/personalize/addFavoritePublication?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225" target="_blank" class="article-tools__favorite btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Add to favorites"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-add-favorite"></i><span class="sr-only">Add to favorites</span></a><a href="/action/addCitationAlert?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225" target="_blank" class="article-tools__citation btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Track Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-alert-bell"></i><span class="sr-only">Track Citations</span></a></div>
</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Myriad infectious organisms can infect the endocardium, myocardium, and pericardium, including bacteria, fungi, parasites, and viruses. Significant cardiac infections are rare in the general population but are associated with high morbidity and mortality as well as increased risk in certain populations, such as the elderly, those undergoing cardiac instrumentation, and intravenous drug abusers. Diagnostic imaging of cardiac infections plays an important role despite its variable sensitivity and specificity, which are due in part to the nonspecific manifestations of the central inflammatory process of infection and the time of onset with respect to the time of imaging. The primary imaging modality remains echocardiography. However, cardiac computed tomography and magnetic resonance (MR) imaging have emerged as the modalities of choice wherever available, especially for diagnosis of complex infectious complications including abscesses, infected prosthetic material, central lines and instruments, and the cryptic manifestations of viral and parasitic diseases. MR imaging can provide functional, morphologic, and prognostic value in a single examination by allowing characterization of inflammatory changes from the acute to chronic stages, including edema and the patterns and extent of delayed gadolinium enhancement. We review the heterogeneous and diverse group of cardiac infections based on their site of primary cardiac involvement with emphasis on their cross-sectional imaging manifestations.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2016</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150225">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150225">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig1.jpeg" height="2089" width="1798" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Diagram of endocardial, myocardial, and pericardial infections. Clusters of black cocci represent the typical endocarditic lesion locations and frequent infectious cause of <i>Staphylococcus</i> species, which commonly appear as an irregular, mobile or fixed mass attached to the endocardium on the low-pressure side of a valve or chordae tendinae or rarely in the posterior left atrial wall, atrial side of the atrioventricular valves, and sites of stenosis or flow jet impact. The red myocardial wall (bottom arrow) represents myocardial infections, which may arise through direct invasion of the endocardium or by hematogenous spread into the myocardium. The purple sac layers (top arrow) distended by yellow effusion fluid represent pericardial infections, which may arise by hematogenous spread into the pericardial layers or their potential space or by direct invasion from an adjacent myocardial infection, an extracardiac infectious process decompressing into the pericardium, or direct seeding from external trauma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig2.jpeg" height="3808" width="2496" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Pathogenic mechanisms of endocardial infection. Two general mechanisms appear to predispose to endocardial infection: mechanical damage or erosion of the endothelium <i>(A)</i> and endothelial inflammation <i>(B)</i>. An area of damaged endothelium or erosion <i>(A)</i> activates the coagulation cascade and facilitates the ability of circulating microbes to adhere to and colonize the site. A second pathway <i>(B)</i> involves inflamed endothelium, where endothelial cells express receptors to which circulating microbes bind and may be endocytosed, or fibrin and other coagulation factors may bind and activate the coagulation cascade. Microbes buried in vegetation become inaccessible to immune cells for clearance. Tissue factor activity <i>(TFA)</i> increases and immune system inflammatory cells produce cytokines, which promote vegetation formation and growth.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig3a.jpeg" height="696" width="882" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Extracardiac manifestations of endocardial infections. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image of the upper chest (lung window) in a 29-year-old man with worsening fever, cough, and chest pain shows multifocal ground-glass and solid nodules, some of which show cavitation changes (arrows). Subsequent echocardiography showed tricuspid valve vegetations, blood cultures grew <i>Staphylococcus epidermis</i>, and the patient admitted to intravenous drug abuse. <b>(b)</b> Axial fluid-attenuated inversion-recovery MR image of the brain in a 72-year-old woman with stroke-like symptoms and fever shows multiple right-sided hyperintense lesions (arrows). Subsequent echocardiography showed prosthetic mitral valve vegetations, and blood cultures were positive for methicillin-resistant <i>Staphylococcus aureus</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig3b.jpeg" height="696" width="593" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Extracardiac manifestations of endocardial infections. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image of the upper chest (lung window) in a 29-year-old man with worsening fever, cough, and chest pain shows multifocal ground-glass and solid nodules, some of which show cavitation changes (arrows). Subsequent echocardiography showed tricuspid valve vegetations, blood cultures grew <i>Staphylococcus epidermis</i>, and the patient admitted to intravenous drug abuse. <b>(b)</b> Axial fluid-attenuated inversion-recovery MR image of the brain in a 72-year-old woman with stroke-like symptoms and fever shows multiple right-sided hyperintense lesions (arrows). Subsequent echocardiography showed prosthetic mitral valve vegetations, and blood cultures were positive for methicillin-resistant <i>Staphylococcus aureus</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig4a.jpeg" height="554" width="919" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Pathology specimens demonstrating active endocarditic infections of cardiac valves and chordae tendineae with typical tissue destruction. <b>(a)</b> Active large bacterial endocarditis vegetations of the aortic valve (opened left ventricular outflow tract [<abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>]), with friable vegetations on the ventricular side of the aortic valve leaflets (arrows). Note the presence of vegetations on the mitral valve surface and chordae tendineae. <b>(b)</b> Active fungal endocarditis of the mitral valve (left ventricular long-axis view). The large vegetation (arrow) has caused functional mitral stenosis. <b>(c)</b> Active bacterial endocarditis of the aortic valve (opened <abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>). Vegetations have caused destruction of one cusp and perforation of another cusp (white plastic bars traverse the leaflet defects). <b>(d)</b> Active <i>Candida</i> endocarditis of the tricuspid valve (surgically excised). The large vegetations have produced leaflet perforations and chordal ruptures (arrows). (Fig 4b, 4c, and 4d courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig4b.jpeg" height="557" width="769" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Pathology specimens demonstrating active endocarditic infections of cardiac valves and chordae tendineae with typical tissue destruction. <b>(a)</b> Active large bacterial endocarditis vegetations of the aortic valve (opened left ventricular outflow tract [<abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>]), with friable vegetations on the ventricular side of the aortic valve leaflets (arrows). Note the presence of vegetations on the mitral valve surface and chordae tendineae. <b>(b)</b> Active fungal endocarditis of the mitral valve (left ventricular long-axis view). The large vegetation (arrow) has caused functional mitral stenosis. <b>(c)</b> Active bacterial endocarditis of the aortic valve (opened <abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>). Vegetations have caused destruction of one cusp and perforation of another cusp (white plastic bars traverse the leaflet defects). <b>(d)</b> Active <i>Candida</i> endocarditis of the tricuspid valve (surgically excised). The large vegetations have produced leaflet perforations and chordal ruptures (arrows). (Fig 4b, 4c, and 4d courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig4c.jpeg" height="554" width="855" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Pathology specimens demonstrating active endocarditic infections of cardiac valves and chordae tendineae with typical tissue destruction. <b>(a)</b> Active large bacterial endocarditis vegetations of the aortic valve (opened left ventricular outflow tract [<abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>]), with friable vegetations on the ventricular side of the aortic valve leaflets (arrows). Note the presence of vegetations on the mitral valve surface and chordae tendineae. <b>(b)</b> Active fungal endocarditis of the mitral valve (left ventricular long-axis view). The large vegetation (arrow) has caused functional mitral stenosis. <b>(c)</b> Active bacterial endocarditis of the aortic valve (opened <abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>). Vegetations have caused destruction of one cusp and perforation of another cusp (white plastic bars traverse the leaflet defects). <b>(d)</b> Active <i>Candida</i> endocarditis of the tricuspid valve (surgically excised). The large vegetations have produced leaflet perforations and chordal ruptures (arrows). (Fig 4b, 4c, and 4d courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig4d.jpeg" height="555" width="1004" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. Pathology specimens demonstrating active endocarditic infections of cardiac valves and chordae tendineae with typical tissue destruction. <b>(a)</b> Active large bacterial endocarditis vegetations of the aortic valve (opened left ventricular outflow tract [<abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>]), with friable vegetations on the ventricular side of the aortic valve leaflets (arrows). Note the presence of vegetations on the mitral valve surface and chordae tendineae. <b>(b)</b> Active fungal endocarditis of the mitral valve (left ventricular long-axis view). The large vegetation (arrow) has caused functional mitral stenosis. <b>(c)</b> Active bacterial endocarditis of the aortic valve (opened <abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>). Vegetations have caused destruction of one cusp and perforation of another cusp (white plastic bars traverse the leaflet defects). <b>(d)</b> Active <i>Candida</i> endocarditis of the tricuspid valve (surgically excised). The large vegetations have produced leaflet perforations and chordal ruptures (arrows). (Fig 4b, 4c, and 4d courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig5a.jpeg" height="646" width="724" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr> of the pulmonary valve in a 37-year-old man with a history of congenital pulmonary valve stenosis and intravenous drug abuse who presented with fever and cough. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal transthoracic echocardiogram shows a large and irregular vegetation attached to the undersurface of the pulmonary valve (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT angiogram corresponding to the plane of the echocardiographic image <b>(a)</b> shows the large and irregular vegetation (black arrow), pulmonic stenosis (white arrows), and poststenotic dilatation of the main pulmonary artery (*). Right ventricle hypertrophy is also evident.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig5b.jpeg" height="646" width="751" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr> of the pulmonary valve in a 37-year-old man with a history of congenital pulmonary valve stenosis and intravenous drug abuse who presented with fever and cough. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal transthoracic echocardiogram shows a large and irregular vegetation attached to the undersurface of the pulmonary valve (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Sagittal CT angiogram corresponding to the plane of the echocardiographic image <b>(a)</b> shows the large and irregular vegetation (black arrow), pulmonic stenosis (white arrows), and poststenotic dilatation of the main pulmonary artery (*). Right ventricle hypertrophy is also evident.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig6a.jpeg" height="608" width="775" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Healed aortic valve <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr> in a 43-year-old man with a history of bicuspid aortic valve (<abbr title="bicuspid aortic valve">BAV</abbr>) and remote <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr>, which resolved after prolonged antibiotic therapy. He presented with increasing dyspnea on exertion. <b>(a)</b> Axial <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image at initial presentation shows a large pseudoaneurysm anterior to the aortic root (yellow arrows), which arose from the <abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>, and multiple regurgitation jets with dephasing artifact (black arrow) (Movies 1, 2). The right coronary artery is displaced anteriorly and superiorly by the pseudoaneurysm (white arrow) (Movie 3). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiogram 4 years later at a comparable level to <b>a</b> shows the <abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr> pseudoaneurysm wall entry (yellow arrows) as well as erosive leaflet destruction along the commissure and chronic perforation of the anterior <abbr title="bicuspid aortic valve">BAV</abbr> leaflet (black arrows) (arrow in axial oblique inset) (Movie 3). White arrow = right coronary artery. <b>(c)</b> Pathologic specimen from a different patient with similar but active bacterial endocarditis of a congenital <abbr title="bicuspid aortic valve">BAV</abbr> (surgically excised). A large vegetation on the nonconjoined cusp produced an 8 × 6-mm perforation with severe aortic regurgitation. (Courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig6b.jpeg" height="607" width="698" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Healed aortic valve <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr> in a 43-year-old man with a history of bicuspid aortic valve (<abbr title="bicuspid aortic valve">BAV</abbr>) and remote <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr>, which resolved after prolonged antibiotic therapy. He presented with increasing dyspnea on exertion. <b>(a)</b> Axial <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image at initial presentation shows a large pseudoaneurysm anterior to the aortic root (yellow arrows), which arose from the <abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>, and multiple regurgitation jets with dephasing artifact (black arrow) (Movies 1, 2). The right coronary artery is displaced anteriorly and superiorly by the pseudoaneurysm (white arrow) (Movie 3). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiogram 4 years later at a comparable level to <b>a</b> shows the <abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr> pseudoaneurysm wall entry (yellow arrows) as well as erosive leaflet destruction along the commissure and chronic perforation of the anterior <abbr title="bicuspid aortic valve">BAV</abbr> leaflet (black arrows) (arrow in axial oblique inset) (Movie 3). White arrow = right coronary artery. <b>(c)</b> Pathologic specimen from a different patient with similar but active bacterial endocarditis of a congenital <abbr title="bicuspid aortic valve">BAV</abbr> (surgically excised). A large vegetation on the nonconjoined cusp produced an 8 × 6-mm perforation with severe aortic regurgitation. (Courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig6c.jpeg" height="868" width="701" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Healed aortic valve <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr> in a 43-year-old man with a history of bicuspid aortic valve (<abbr title="bicuspid aortic valve">BAV</abbr>) and remote <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr>, which resolved after prolonged antibiotic therapy. He presented with increasing dyspnea on exertion. <b>(a)</b> Axial <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> MR image at initial presentation shows a large pseudoaneurysm anterior to the aortic root (yellow arrows), which arose from the <abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>, and multiple regurgitation jets with dephasing artifact (black arrow) (Movies 1, 2). The right coronary artery is displaced anteriorly and superiorly by the pseudoaneurysm (white arrow) (Movie 3). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiogram 4 years later at a comparable level to <b>a</b> shows the <abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr> pseudoaneurysm wall entry (yellow arrows) as well as erosive leaflet destruction along the commissure and chronic perforation of the anterior <abbr title="bicuspid aortic valve">BAV</abbr> leaflet (black arrows) (arrow in axial oblique inset) (Movie 3). White arrow = right coronary artery. <b>(c)</b> Pathologic specimen from a different patient with similar but active bacterial endocarditis of a congenital <abbr title="bicuspid aortic valve">BAV</abbr> (surgically excised). A large vegetation on the nonconjoined cusp produced an 8 × 6-mm perforation with severe aortic regurgitation. (Courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig7a.jpeg" height="701" width="711" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Congenital aortic stenosis and <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr> in a 20-year-old man with a history of congenital aortic stenosis, multiple prior surgeries, and bioprosthetic aortic valve replacement. He presented with fever and atypical chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic valve annulus shows perivalvular extension of <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr>, including a complex pseudoaneurysm (*) and complex aortic root abscess (white arrows) (Movie 4). Note the course of the right coronary artery (yellow arrow) under the sternum with pectus excavatum deformity. Blood cultures grew coagulase-negative <i>S aureus</i>. <b>(b)</b> Left anterior oblique projection of three-dimensional volume rendering from the CT angiography dataset shows the anatomic relationship of the complex aortic root abscess, pseudoaneurysm, and course of the right coronary artery (yellow arrow) with respect to the sternum and sternotomy wires (white arrow). (See also Fig E2 and Movie 5.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig7b.jpeg" height="700" width="764" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Congenital aortic stenosis and <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr> in a 20-year-old man with a history of congenital aortic stenosis, multiple prior surgeries, and bioprosthetic aortic valve replacement. He presented with fever and atypical chest pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic valve annulus shows perivalvular extension of <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr>, including a complex pseudoaneurysm (*) and complex aortic root abscess (white arrows) (Movie 4). Note the course of the right coronary artery (yellow arrow) under the sternum with pectus excavatum deformity. Blood cultures grew coagulase-negative <i>S aureus</i>. <b>(b)</b> Left anterior oblique projection of three-dimensional volume rendering from the CT angiography dataset shows the anatomic relationship of the complex aortic root abscess, pseudoaneurysm, and course of the right coronary artery (yellow arrow) with respect to the sternum and sternotomy wires (white arrow). (See also Fig E2and Movie 5.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig8.jpeg" height="612" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. <abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr> pseudoaneurysm in a 42-year-old man with fever, chest pain, and a history of intravenous drug abuse. Echocardiography showed an <abbr title="left ventricular outflow tract">LVOT</abbr> pseudoaneurysm and incompletely visualized vegetations on a bioprosthetic aortic valve. Sagittal oblique CT angiogram shows a large and complex posterior outflow pseoudoaneurysm (arrows) with multiple vegetations in the pseudoaneurysm and the bioprosthetic aortic valve (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig9a.jpeg" height="682" width="658" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Active <abbr title="prosthetic valve endocarditis">PVE</abbr> in an 86-year-old man with fever of unknown origin and a remote history of aortic valve replacement. Sagittal CT angiogram <b>(a)</b> and axial oblique CT angiogram along the prosthetic valve annulus <b>(b)</b> show a complex pseudoaneurysm extending around the annulus (thin arrows in <b>a</b>, arrows in <b>b</b>), undermining the valve, and an ascending aorta fluid collection (thick arrow in <b>a</b>). Dynamic cine image analysis demonstrated prosthetic valve annulus motion (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig9b.jpeg" height="681" width="662" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Active <abbr title="prosthetic valve endocarditis">PVE</abbr> in an 86-year-old man with fever of unknown origin and a remote history of aortic valve replacement. Sagittal CT angiogram <b>(a)</b> and axial oblique CT angiogram along the prosthetic valve annulus <b>(b)</b> show a complex pseudoaneurysm extending around the annulus (thin arrows in <b>a</b>, arrows in <b>b</b>), undermining the valve, and an ascending aorta fluid collection (thick arrow in <b>a</b>). Dynamic cine image analysis demonstrated prosthetic valve annulus motion (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig10a.jpeg" height="557" width="649" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Prosthetic material infection in a 57-year-old man with fever of unknown origin and a history of aortic root and ascending aorta replacement graft. Sagittal thin-slab maximum intensity projection CT angiogram of the aorta <b>(a)</b> and axial CT angiogram at the level of the main pulmonary artery <b>(b)</b> show an ascending aorta fluid collection surrounding the graft (thick arrows in <b>a</b>, arrows in <b>b</b>), a graft pseudoaneurysm (thin arrow in <b>a</b>), aneurysmal dilatation of the brachiocephalic artery (* in <b>a</b>), and prosthetic aortic valve vegetations (not shown). Prosthetic material calcifications are present at the aortic root.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig10b.jpeg" height="555" width="673" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Prosthetic material infection in a 57-year-old man with fever of unknown origin and a history of aortic root and ascending aorta replacement graft. Sagittal thin-slab maximum intensity projection CT angiogram of the aorta <b>(a)</b> and axial CT angiogram at the level of the main pulmonary artery <b>(b)</b> show an ascending aorta fluid collection surrounding the graft (thick arrows in <b>a</b>, arrows in <b>b</b>), a graft pseudoaneurysm (thin arrow in <b>a</b>), aneurysmal dilatation of the brachiocephalic artery (* in <b>a</b>), and prosthetic aortic valve vegetations (not shown). Prosthetic material calcifications are present at the aortic root.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig11a.jpeg" height="626" width="699" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Prosthetic mitral valve <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr> in a 57-year-old man with severe bacteremia and sepsis and a history of mitral valve replacement. Sagittal CT angiogram <b>(a)</b> and coronal oblique CT angiogram along the mitral valve annulus plane <b>(b)</b> show a large irregular vegetation (arrow in <b>a</b>) adherent to the prosthetic valve (arrow in <b>b</b>) and extending into the left atrium (arrow in <b>a</b>). Blood cultures were positive for methicillin-resistant <i>S aureus</i>, and the patient was treated surgically.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig11b.jpeg" height="625" width="626" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Prosthetic mitral valve <abbr title="infective endocarditis">IE</abbr> in a 57-year-old man with severe bacteremia and sepsis and a history of mitral valve replacement. Sagittal CT angiogram <b>(a)</b> and coronal oblique CT angiogram along the mitral valve annulus plane <b>(b)</b> show a large irregular vegetation (arrow in <b>a</b>) adherent to the prosthetic valve (arrow in <b>b</b>) and extending into the left atrium (arrow in <b>a</b>). Blood cultures were positive for methicillin-resistant <i>S aureus</i>, and the patient was treated surgically.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig12a.jpeg" height="688" width="648" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Noninfectious endocardial lesions. <b>(a)</b> Libman-Sacks endocarditis in a 69-year-old woman undergoing evaluation for coronary artery disease who had a history of multiple mini-strokes and abnormal but inconclusive autoimmune panels. Left ventricle three-chamber view from CT angiography shows strandlike elongated vegetations arising from the aortic valve (arrow), compatible with Libman-Sacks endocarditis. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique CT angiogram at the level of the aorta in a 50-year-old woman presenting with a stroke and new heart murmur shows a polypoid vegetation-like mass arising from the undersurface of the aortic valve (arrow). The mass proved to be a papillary fibroelastoma. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph from another patient with an aortic valve papillary fibroelastoma shows a papillary lesion with avascular and acellular cores that have a central matrix containing mucopolysaccharides. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) The surface of the papillary fronds is covered by single or multiple layers of endothelial cells (inset; original magnification, ×40).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig12b.jpeg" height="689" width="675" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Noninfectious endocardial lesions. <b>(a)</b> Libman-Sacks endocarditis in a 69-year-old woman undergoing evaluation for coronary artery disease who had a history of multiple mini-strokes and abnormal but inconclusive autoimmune panels. Left ventricle three-chamber view from CT angiography shows strandlike elongated vegetations arising from the aortic valve (arrow), compatible with Libman-Sacks endocarditis. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique CT angiogram at the level of the aorta in a 50-year-old woman presenting with a stroke and new heart murmur shows a polypoid vegetation-like mass arising from the undersurface of the aortic valve (arrow). The mass proved to be a papillary fibroelastoma. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph from another patient with an aortic valve papillary fibroelastoma shows a papillary lesion with avascular and acellular cores that have a central matrix containing mucopolysaccharides. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) The surface of the papillary fronds is covered by single or multiple layers of endothelial cells (inset; original magnification, ×40).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig12c.jpeg" height="875" width="899" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Noninfectious endocardial lesions. <b>(a)</b> Libman-Sacks endocarditis in a 69-year-old woman undergoing evaluation for coronary artery disease who had a history of multiple mini-strokes and abnormal but inconclusive autoimmune panels. Left ventricle three-chamber view from CT angiography shows strandlike elongated vegetations arising from the aortic valve (arrow), compatible with Libman-Sacks endocarditis. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique CT angiogram at the level of the aorta in a 50-year-old woman presenting with a stroke and new heart murmur shows a polypoid vegetation-like mass arising from the undersurface of the aortic valve (arrow). The mass proved to be a papillary fibroelastoma. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph from another patient with an aortic valve papillary fibroelastoma shows a papillary lesion with avascular and acellular cores that have a central matrix containing mucopolysaccharides. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) The surface of the papillary fronds is covered by single or multiple layers of endothelial cells (inset; original magnification, ×40).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig13.jpeg" height="717" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Bacterial myocarditis and cardiac abscess in a 27-year-old man with rapidly progressing severe upper back pain, fever for 2 days, and a history of indwelling central lines. Axial CT angiogram shows a markedly thickened hypoattenuating left ventricular wall (black and white arrows) including the basal to mid interventricular septum and basal free wall. The apical wall is normal in thickness and enhancement (yellow arrows). Soon after presentation, complete heart block and sepsis developed, and a transvenous pacemaker was placed. Despite aggressive supportive measures, the patient died; autopsy showed an <i>S aureus</i>–positive cardiac abscess and pyomyocarditis involving most of the left ventricle sparing the apex. A small pericardial effusion, bilateral pleural effusions, and atelectatic opacities are also evident.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig14.jpeg" height="755" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Bacterial myocarditis in a 10-year-old boy with acute <i>Mycoplasma</i> myocarditis who presented with chest pain. Initial evaluation was positive for elevated cardiac enzymes. Postcontrast T1-weighted inversion-recovery MR image (horizontal four-chamber view) shows nodular subepicardial delayed myocardial enhancement along the posterior and lateral walls of the left ventricle (arrows). Serologic studies were positive for <i>Mycoplasma pneumoniae</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig15.jpeg" height="678" width="794" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Acute myocarditis in a 17-year-old girl. Horizontal long-axis turbo inversion-recovery magnitude image shows extensive hyperintense signal throughout the left ventricular apical, distal lateral, and distal septal myocardium, compatible with myocardial edema. The high signal intensity extends to and involves the right ventricular apex (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig16.jpeg" height="679" width="779" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Viral myocarditis in a 54-year-old woman with general malaise, weakness, and palpitations with reported common cold symptoms 4 weeks earlier. Postcontrast T1-weighted inversion-recovery MR image (long-axis two-chamber view) shows patchy primarily epicardial <abbr title="delayed gadolinium enhancement">DGE</abbr> (arrows) in the lateral wall in a noncoronary distribution.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig17a.jpeg" height="852" width="655" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Parasitic myocarditis in a 72-year-old woman with Chagas cardiomyopathy. Balanced <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and postcontrast T1-weighted inversion-recovery <b>(b)</b> MR images show a posterolateral left ventricular aneurysm with transmural <abbr title="delayed gadolinium enhancement">DGE</abbr> (white arrow) and a small focus of delayed midmyocardial enhancement in the basal interventricular septum (black arrow). Coronary angiography showed no clinically important atherosclerotic disease. (Case courtesy of Monica Ocampo, MD, Fundacion Cardiovascular de Colombia, Floridablanca, Colombia.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig17b.jpeg" height="857" width="660" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Parasitic myocarditis in a 72-year-old woman with Chagas cardiomyopathy. Balanced <abbr title="steady-state free precession">SSFP</abbr> <b>(a)</b> and postcontrast T1-weighted inversion-recovery <b>(b)</b> MR images show a posterolateral left ventricular aneurysm with transmural <abbr title="delayed gadolinium enhancement">DGE</abbr> (white arrow) and a small focus of delayed midmyocardial enhancement in the basal interventricular septum (black arrow). Coronary angiography showed no clinically important atherosclerotic disease. (Case courtesy of Monica Ocampo, MD, Fundacion Cardiovascular de Colombia, Floridablanca, Colombia.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig18a.jpeg" height="815" width="857" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Bacterial pericarditis. <b>(a)</b> A 48-year-old man with fever, chest pain, no prior trauma, and increasing shortness of breath. CT image shows a large pericardial fluid and gas collection with a gas-fluid level (arrows) from gas-producing bacteria, which on drainage showed purulent malodorous material. <b>(b)</b> Persistent symptoms of bacterial pericarditis in a 40-year-old man. Axial T1-weighted dual inversion-recovery MR image shows a pericardial collection and pericardial thickening (black arrows), complex loculated fluid, and fibrous strands (white arrow) over the right anterolateral pericardium with mass effect on the right chambers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig18b.jpeg" height="815" width="918" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Bacterial pericarditis. <b>(a)</b> A 48-year-old man with fever, chest pain, no prior trauma, and increasing shortness of breath. CT image shows a large pericardial fluid and gas collection with a gas-fluid level (arrows) from gas-producing bacteria, which on drainage showed purulent malodorous material. <b>(b)</b> Persistent symptoms of bacterial pericarditis in a 40-year-old man. Axial T1-weighted dual inversion-recovery MR image shows a pericardial collection and pericardial thickening (black arrows), complex loculated fluid, and fibrous strands (white arrow) over the right anterolateral pericardium with mass effect on the right chambers.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig19a.jpeg" height="582" width="650" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Pericarditis without and with effusion. <b>(a)</b> A 39-year-old man with increasing episodes of chest pain. Axial nonenhanced CT image shows segmental areas of irregular pericardial thickening over the anterior pericardium (short arrows) and no significant pericardial effusion. Long arrow = areas of normal pericardial thickness. <b>(b)</b> A 50-year-old man with worsening symptoms of pericarditis. Axial CT image with intravenous contrast material shows visceral (black arrow) and parietal (white arrow) pericardial thickening and enhancement with a moderate-sized pericardial effusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig19b.jpeg" height="582" width="675" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Pericarditis without and with effusion. <b>(a)</b> A 39-year-old man with increasing episodes of chest pain. Axial nonenhanced CT image shows segmental areas of irregular pericardial thickening over the anterior pericardium (short arrows) and no significant pericardial effusion. Long arrow = areas of normal pericardial thickness. <b>(b)</b> A 50-year-old man with worsening symptoms of pericarditis. Axial CT image with intravenous contrast material shows visceral (black arrow) and parietal (white arrow) pericardial thickening and enhancement with a moderate-sized pericardial effusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig20a.jpeg" height="542" width="661" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Effusive-constrictive pericarditis in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis postcontrast T1-weighted inversion-recovery MR image shows diffuse thickening and enhancement of the visceral (white arrow) and parietal (black arrow) pericardium. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis real-time still cine MR image during diastole while performing the Valsalva maneuver shows flattening of the interventricular septum (arrow), in keeping with increased ventricular interdependence in the setting of constrictive physiology (diastolic septal bounce). Note the small circumferential pericardial effusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig20b.jpeg" height="543" width="661" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Effusive-constrictive pericarditis in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis postcontrast T1-weighted inversion-recovery MR image shows diffuse thickening and enhancement of the visceral (white arrow) and parietal (black arrow) pericardium. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis real-time still cine MR image during diastole while performing the Valsalva maneuver shows flattening of the interventricular septum (arrow), in keeping with increased ventricular interdependence in the setting of constrictive physiology (diastolic septal bounce). Note the small circumferential pericardial effusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig21.jpeg" height="657" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. Chronic constrictive pericarditis in a 52-year-old man with slow but progressive dyspnea on exertion, who was unable to complete a cardiac stress test and denied chest pain. Thin-slab maximum intensity projection CT angiogram (long-axis four-chamber view) shows encircling linear calcifications and a band of pericardial thickening along the atrioventricular groove (arrows) with associated tubular ventricles, enlarged atria, and ventricular interdependence at cine image analysis (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150225/asset/images/large/rg.2016150225.fig22.jpeg" height="827" width="950" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. Acute parasitic pericarditis in a 50-year-old man with worsening upper abdominal pain who presented with new-onset dyspnea. CT image with oral and intravenous contrast material shows a large abscess in the left liver lobe (arrows in inset), which had eroded through the diaphragm and decompressed into the pericardial space, producing a large pericardial effusion (arrows). Emergent surgical pericardial drainage demonstrated extensive and spontaneous drainage of purulent material, which was positive for <i>Entamoeba histolytica</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150225&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Moreillon P, Que YA. Infective endocarditis. <em>Lancet</em> 2004;363(9403):139–149.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(03)15266-X">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14726169/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lo